sdp/verification/t-026@20260427t001208z-verify.md:12:`_ARC_FRAGMENTS` is defined as a `Final[dict[str, str]]` at module level (line 49–56), keyed by arc phase name. All six phases from the task spec are present: Emergence, Crystallization, Divination, Convergence, Conversation, Reflection. The fallback is `_DEFAULT_ARC_FRAGMENT = "in-progress"` used via `_ARC_FRAGMENTS.get(str(arc_phase), _DEFAULT_ARC_FRAGMENT)` in `_prompt()`. The fragment is injected between the mode fragment and the mood adjective. All acceptance criteria met.
sdp/verification/t-026@20260427t001208z-verify.md:16:All 5 `ARC_PHASES` from `procedural_arc.py` (Divination, Emergence, Conversation, Convergence, Crystallization) are covered, plus Reflection which is in the task spec but not yet in `ARC_PHASES` — this is forward-compatible. The test `test_arc_fragments_cover_procedural_arc_phase_names` enforces the subset relationship via `{phase.name for phase in ARC_PHASES} <= set(_ARC_FRAGMENTS)`. Fallback path is explicitly tested by `test_unknown_arc_phase_uses_in_progress_prompt_fragment`. No gaps found.
sdp/verification/t-026@20260427t001208z-verify.md:20:Implementation follows the existing `_MODE_FRAGMENTS` lookup pattern. Dict is `Final`, values are short strings, lookup uses `.get()` with a default — consistent with how `_MODE_FRAGMENTS` is structured. The `_DEFAULT_ARC_FRAGMENT` was changed from `"in-progress material"` to `"in-progress"` in this commit; the test reflects the new value and is internally consistent.
sdp/verification/t-026@20260427t001208z-verify.md:30:**Candidate hardening items (bootstrap_identity / startup flow):** These hardening checks were auto-generated from a recurring failure pattern in prior tasks and concern startup identity bootstrapping — outside the scope of T-026, which is a pure data/conditioning change with no startup logic. No action required for this task.
sdp/verification/t-026@20260427t001208z-verify.md:40:No action required. All acceptance criteria met, all tests pass. The `_DEFAULT_ARC_FRAGMENT` change from `"in-progress material"` to `"in-progress"` is cosmetically inconsistent with the original neutral phrasing but the test suite locks it in — leave as-is unless there is a product reason to prefer the longer form.
